{
  "text": "Genetic marker-assisted screening of good egg-bearers helps to sort out the genetic background of lowered quality of eggs; however, DNA markers will not help to determine postovulatory age-related features occurring in an egg batch. Under conditions of commercial production, it is not possible to determine precisely the postovulatory age of every batch of eggs. Previous studies on fish egg transcriptome (reviewed by [CITATION_1] ) have suggested the potential of transcriptomics for evaluating embryonic developmental competence. Maternal transcripts are essential during the early embryonic development and for zygotic genome activation [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The level of maternally stocked transcripts, such as nucleoplasmin, tubulin β, insulin-like growth factor 1, keratin 8, or prohibitin 2, are linked to the egg quality in rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss) [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Maternally inherited nucleoplasmin is suggested as essential for zebrafish egg developmental competence [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "205784283",
    "[CITATION_2]": "4451097",
    "[CITATION_3]": "1795214",
    "[CITATION_4]": "25629028",
